Welcome to Pharos

########################################################################
# Introduction
########################################################################

Pharos is an operating system designed for real-time systems. Its primary 
objectives are:

•	Security: Developed with security in mind. Implemented the notion 
of partitions, similar to the ARINC653, with space partition and with 
some additional enhancements in the time partitioning. Besides protecting
each partition with the hardware Memory Management Unit, to avoid invalid
 memory accesses, partitions in Pharos operate in user mode, which 
renders impossible any attempt to control the CPU.

•	Certifiably: Developed with the intention to reduce the future 
certification burden of the system where Pharos will be used. Considering
some of the requirements of the strictest standards (e.g DO178), like the
Cyclomatic Number, Nesting Levels, Comments and MISRA rules. Pharos is 
composed approximately of 10K lines of code.

•	Mixed Criticality: Applications with different criticality levels
(Level A, B, C, D, etc) can coexist in the same processor. Pharos 
guarantees the independence and the isolation of each partition by 
providing native support to sporadic, periodic and aperiodic threads 
under a fixed-priority preemptive scheduler and includes WCET protection 
(a thread is not allowed to execute for more time than it should). That 
means that a non-critical partition can have a high priority thread and 
Pharos will still fully ensure that lower priority threads will still 
run, even if the non-critical thread is on an infinite loop. Pharos also 
provides elegant and fast inter-partition communication and 
synchronization solutions. Each partition can define filter functions 
which state who is allowed to communicate with it. The improvements on 
this topic are so extensive that is hard to summarize them. We encourage 
you to read the User Manual for more information.

•	Determinism: Pharos provides hard real-time determinism. Each 
Pharos call will take a limited amount of time to execute and is, in a 
few cases, maximized to O(Log(N)) of the number of objects in the system 
(for example, number of threads).

Pharos is open source and available in Sourceforge 
(https://sourceforge.net/projects/rtospharos/). It is licensed under the 
Apache License 2.0, meaning that you can use on your commercial or 
non-commercial projects.

The current supported platforms are:

•	ARM926EJ-S CPU -> Versatilepb board with an  for a QEMU emulator 
•	Cortex-R5  CPU -> LAUNCHXL2-570LC43 board with a Texas Instruments CPU (TMS570LC4357)
          Note: this board is not currently supported since our own board is broken (flash)
•	Cortex-M4  CPU -> EK_TM4C129EXL board with a Texas Instruments CPU (TM4C129ENCPDT)
•	Cortex-M4  CPU -> STM32F469I-DISCOVERY board with an ST CPU (STM32F469NIH6)
•	Cortex-A53 CPU -> Raspberry Pi3 in Aarch64 (qemu version only)
•	RISC-V CPU     -> Quad-core RISC-V 64 bits Qemu Virt board (qemu version only)

