# Documentation
########################################################################

For a complete user manual, go to 

https://sourceforge.net/projects/rtospharos/files/

select the Pharos release you want and download the UserManualx.x.x.tar.gz.
In this user manual you will find a document with the full description of
Pharos and source code of fully functioning examples.

########################################################################
# Hello World
########################################################################

To get your first application running on Pharos, please go to 

https://sourceforge.net/p/rtospharos/wiki/Hello%20world/

or check the examples in the user manual (see "Documentation" above).

You can easily place some examples working on qemu for the versatilepb
board.

########################################################################
# Installation
########################################################################

For detailed information about the installation procedure please refer to
the Pharos User Manual.

/*
 * 1-Host
 */

For host machine please install a Linux based operating system (e.g 
Debian like OS in 64 bits).

Please install the following packages:

# Package containing an informational list of packages which are 
# considered essential for building Debian packages, including GCC, 
# necessary for building the cross-compiler.
apt-get install build-essential 

# (Optional) C library in i386 platform in case you have installed the 
# amd64 architecture. This libc:i386 will be used by Texas Instruments 
# applications for running the boards.
dpkg --add-architecture i386
apt-get update
apt-get install libc6:i386

# Packages necessary to install the cross-compilers and the Qemu for 
# all platforms
apt-get install texinfo zlib1g-dev libglib2.0-dev libpixman-1-dev \
flex bison

/*
 * 2-Extract Pharos and User Manual
 */

export PHAROS_FILE_PATH=~/Pharos

mkdir $PHAROS_FILE_PATH

cp pharos[X.Y.Z].tar.gz $PHAROS_FILE_PATH

cp UserManual[X.Y.Z].tar.gz $PHAROS_FILE_PATH

cd $PHAROS_FILE_PATH

tar xvfz pharos[X.Y.Z].tar.gz

tar xvfz UserManual[X.Y.Z].tar.gz

/*
 * 3-Toolchain
 */            
cd $PHAROS_FILE_PATH
make -f Makefile.cross-compiler build-crosscompiler-all


/*
 * 5-Build qemu (optional) 
 */
make -f Makefile.cross-compiler qemu

/*
 * 6-Export the cross-compiler variables
 */
source export.sh


/*
 * 4-Build Pharos and Examples 
 */
cd $PHAROS_FILE_PATH/examples/thread/example1

make CONF=arm-v5-926ejs-versatilepb-qemu-debug

/*
 * 5-Execute an example with QEMU
 */
qemu-system-arm -M versatilepb -m 128M -nographic -kernel \
dist/arm-v5-926ejs-versatilepb-qemu-debug/GNU-Linux/application.bin

/*
 * 6-Further steps and information 
 */

For detailed infrmation about the installation procedure please refer to
the Pharos User Manual.

########################################################################
# Datasheet
########################################################################

It was designed for Secure systems. This means that it supports real-time applications:

•	Fixed-priority preemptive scheduler
•	Quick critical sections (small amount of time where interrupts are disabled)
•	Semaphore with ceiling protocol
•	Priority queues -> the highest priority thread blocked on an object (e.g. semaphore) will be the first one to get it)
•	Native support for periodic threads (real-time threads)
•	Native support for sporadic threads (real-time threads)
•	Native support for aperiodic threads (non real-time threads)
•	Deadline monitoring
•	Thread execution time monitoring - WCET - (and prevent the thread from executing more time than it is configured to)
•	Low interrupt latency (time interval from the moment the interrupt is triggered in hardware and the instant the application ISR is invoked)
•	Low context switch time
•	Low flash requirements (~90 KiB for the full Pharos in flash)
•	Low RAM requirements (~80 KiB of RAM required for Cortex-R5)
•	and more

The application can be divided into partitions, where each partition is 
composed by a set of objects (threads, semaphores, queues, etc), and most 
importantly, each partition cannot damage the execution of another 
partition. This damage prevention is done both at:

•	Memory Level Partition: a thread from one partition cannot access 
the memory area of another partition

•	Time Level Partition: each thread cannot execute for more time than it is allowed to

Each thread is executed in user mode and therefore prevented perform "special" hardware 
operations like changing the memory management (MMU/MPU) settings.

Drivers in Pharos are executed as normal partitions. However, since drivers 
have low-level hardware requirements that cannot always be meet in user 
mode, Pharos features some special mechanisms so that drivers can be 
executed (WITHOUT switching to supervisor mode). These are:

•	Critical sections: a partition can be configured to have a function 
that can be executed while interrupts are disabled (note that the function 
is executed in user mode)

•	Interrupt management:
	• Your application can configure the priority (and whatever parameters
          the CPU supports, such as "wake on interrupt") of each interrupt
	• a partition can be configured to be able to install a pre-configured ISR handler

•	I/O memory access: a partition can be configured to have access to 
specific memory addresses (can be normal RAM memory or a device configuration registers)


Besides the "standard" objects that Pharos provides for 
communication/synchronization inside a partition (such as queues, events, 
semaphores, etc), Pharos also provides inter-partition communication and 
synchronization features:

•	Resource: a synchronization mechanism that uses a semaphore ceiling 
that allows the execution of a partition configured function in mutual 
exclusion. To prevent a thread from having a WCET timeout inside the 
execution of the function, a check is made before the call is made to verify 
that the thread has enough execution time

•	Heavy weight queue: copy messages from one partition to another. 
Good for small messages

•	Channel: "move" messages from one partition to another without copying 
it. This is done through careful manipulation of the MMU/MPU. Good for big 
messages, but incurs in a memory performance penalization since the messages 
must be aligned and have a size that fits the requirements of the MMU (for 
example, alignment to 4KiB and size multiple of 4KiB) or the MPU (for example, 
in ARM, the MPU PMSR requires the alignment to be at least equal to the size 
of the message)

•	Inter-partition calls: Pharos allows each partition to define a set 
of functions that can be accessed by other partitions. Furthermore, instead 
of having the fixed format of the typical drivers calls (e.g. open, read, 
write, control) which a fixed set of inputs and outputs, which will force to 
the use of casts (e.g. "(struct termios *)"), Pharos allows the partition to 
create its own function with any set of parameters (with few limitations)

•	I/O memory access: a partition can be configured to have access to 
specific memory addresses. This can be used for drivers but also for inter-partition 
communication through a shared memory area

•	Shared memory: There is a memory region that any partition can have 
access to

Since partitions can contain errors and call the inter-partition objects of 
another partition can possibly damage it, Pharos introduces the concept of 
"filters". A filter is a function, configured by the application for each 
inter-partition object, invoked before the inter-partition object is accessed,
that can allow or deny access to that object. This allows the re-usage of 
generic partitions that implement, for example, drivers (e.g. CAN driver, 
SPI driver) and the application that uses these generic partitions can define, 
through the use of filters, which partitions can use these generic partitions
and when. Note also that filters functions are executed within a special stack
and on the context of the partition trying to be accessed. This is to ensure 
that the calling partition does not have permissions to perform any kind of
"attack" and gain permissions to the filter. Also, this filter function is 
executed within the time execution of the calling thread. So if the same thread
tries to gain access to a object by accessing it 1000s of times, it will only
exaust its on execution time.

